Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to implement a small, reliable serverless API with per-tenant isolation, idempotent writes, and TTL in Cosmos DB. It also checks basic validation, simple retries, and test strategy.

Key Concepts

- Azure Functions HTTP trigger and route parameters
- Cosmos DB partitioning by tenantId and idempotent upserts
- JSON payload validation against a minimal schema
- TTL retention in Cosmos DB containers
- Basic retry/backoff and error handling
- Unit and end-to-end testing with local emulation

Code Example

```javascript
// Example outline for the HTTP POST handler
module.exports = async function (context, req) {
  const tenantId = req.params.tenantId;
  const body = req.body;
  // basic validation: eventId required, payload present
  if (!tenantId || !body || !body.eventId) {
    context.res = { status: 400, body: 'Invalid payload' };
    return;
  }
  const item = {
    id: body.eventId,
    tenantId,
    payload: body,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString()
  };
  // upsert to Cosmos DB (idempotent by using eventId as id)
  await cosmosClient.database(DATABASE).container(CONTAINER)
    .items.upsert(item);
  context.res = { status: 200, body: { ok: true } };
};
```

