- How would you evolve the schema when new fields are introduced while preserving backward compatibility?

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a high-throughput, tenant-isolated streaming validation pipeline with dynamic schemas and robust failure handling at cloud scale.

## Key Concepts

- Tenant-scoped JSON Schema versioning and caching
- Durable Functions orchestration patterns and fan-out/fan-in
- Idempotent writes and dead-lettering strategies
- End-to-end latency optimization and distributed tracing
- Schema evolution and backward compatibility

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudocode: schema fetch and cache
const getTenantSchema = async (tenantId, version) => {
  const cacheKey = `${tenantId}:${version}`;
  let schema = await cache.get(cacheKey);

  if (!schema) {
    schema = await blobStorage.get(`schemas/${tenantId}/v${version}.json`);
    await cache.set(cacheKey, schema, { ttl: 300 }); // 5 minutes
  }

  return schema;
};

// Validation orchestrator
const validateEventsOrchestrator = function* (context) {
  const events = context.getInput();
  const tasks = events.map(event => 
    context.df.callActivity('validateEvent', event)
  );

  const results = yield context.df.Task.all(tasks);

  const validEvents = results.filter(r => r.isValid);
  const anomalies = results.filter(r => !r.isValid);

  yield context.df.callActivity('persistValidEvents', validEvents);
  yield context.df.callActivity('emitAnomalies', anomalies);
};
```

## Testing Strategy

- Unit tests for individual validation functions
- Integration tests for schema evolution scenarios
- Load testing with 300k events/sec to verify latency targets
- Chaos testing for failure scenarios and rollback procedures
- Tenant isolation verification tests

## Rollback Strategy

- Maintain previous schema versions in blob storage
- Use feature flags to enable/disable new schema versions
- Implement canary deployments for schema changes
- Monitor validation success rates and auto-rollback on threshold breaches

