- Azure Storage Queue semantics and poison messages
- Blob Storage for produced assets
- Retries with exponential backoff and observability with Application Insights

## Code Example

```javascript
// Pseudo-idempotent processing sketch
module.exports = async function (context, queueMessage) {
  const { tenantId, jobId, imageUrl } = queueMessage;

  // Check idempotency - skip if already processed
  const existingJob = await cosmosDB.readJob(tenantId, jobId);
  if (existingJob && existingJob.status === 'completed') {
    context.log.info(`Job ${jobId} already completed, skipping`);
    return;
  }

  try {
    // Update status to processing
    await cosmosDB.updateJobStatus(tenantId, jobId, 'processing');

    // Process image
    const resizedImage = await imageProcessor.resize(imageUrl);

    // Store result in tenant-specific blob path
    const blobUrl = await blobStorage.upload(
      `tenants/${tenantId}/processed/${jobId}.jpg`,
      resizedImage
    );

    // Mark as completed
    await cosmosDB.updateJobStatus(tenantId, jobId, 'completed', blobUrl);

  } catch (error) {
    // Log error and update status
    context.log.error(`Failed to process job ${jobId}:`, error);
    await cosmosDB.updateJobStatus(tenantId, jobId, 'failed', null, error.message);
    throw error; // Re-throw for queue retry
  }
};
```

## Implementation Notes

- **Data Models**: Cosmos DB document with tenantId partition key, jobId, status, and metadata
- **Isolation**: Tenant-specific blob paths and Cosmos DB queries ensure data separation
- **Idempotency**: Job status check prevents duplicate processing
- **Observability**: Application Insights tracks function execution and errors
- **Retry Strategy**: Built-in queue retries with exponential backoff for transient failures

